Module 2: Authentication, Authorization, And Accounting

Managing who or what has access to information
Access Control: Security controls that manage who can access what, ensuring:
âœ”ï¸ Confidentiality â€“ Protecting sensitive information.
âœ”ï¸ Integrity â€“ Preventing unauthorized modifications.
âœ”ï¸ Availability â€“ Ensuring users can access what they need.

It is broken down by the AAA framework (authentication, authorization, accounting)
Authentication â†’ Who are you? (Verifying identity)
Authorization â†’ What can you access? (Permissions)
Accounting â†’ What did you do? (Logging & tracking)

-
Authentication
SSO 
A technology that combines multiple logins into one, allowing users to access several applications with a single authentication process.
âœ”ï¸ Better User Experience: No need to remember multiple passwords.
âœ”ï¸ Stronger Security: Reduces attack surfaces by centralizing authentication.
âœ”ï¸ Cost Efficiency: Simplifies IT management & lowers password reset costs.
âœ”ï¸ Prevents Password Fatigue: Users donâ€™t reuse weak passwords across multiple sites.

Security Features of SSO
âœ”ï¸ Centralized Authentication: Only one secure login instead of many weak passwords.
âœ”ï¸ Reduces Phishing Risks: Users log in less often, reducing the chance of falling for fake login pages.
âœ”ï¸ Uses Secure Tokens Instead of Passwords: Applications donâ€™t store passwordsâ€”only trust temporary tokens issued by the IdP.
âœ”ï¸ Supports Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA): Can add extra layers (e.g., SMS codes, biometrics, security keys).

How SSO Works (Step-by-Step)
1ï¸âƒ£ User Requests Access
You enter credentials (username & password) on a site (e.g., Gmail).
Instead of Gmail verifying them, it redirects you to an Identity Provider (IdP) (e.g., Googleâ€™s authentication system).
2ï¸âƒ£ Identity Provider Verifies Your Identity
IdP checks your credentials & confirms who you are.
If correct, the IdP issues an encrypted token containing your authentication details.
3ï¸âƒ£ Token Sent to the Service Provider (SP)
Gmail (the Service Provider) receives this secure token from the IdP.
Instead of storing or handling your password, Gmail trusts the IdPâ€™s verification.
4ï¸âƒ£ Access Granted Across Services
Now, when you visit Google Drive or YouTube, they reuse the existing token instead of asking for a password again.

Limitations of SSO & How to Mitigate Risks
âŒ Single Point of Failure: If an attacker gets your SSO password, they can access everything.
âœ”ï¸ Solution: Use Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) to add another layer of security.

âŒ Remote Access Risks: Cloud-based SSO can be harder to secure for remote users.
âœ”ï¸ Solution: Implement Zero Trust Security (always verify, never assume trust).


